# Chapter 1
WE RECOGNIZE on the earth the rolling contours of country fields, the windscorched green and brown tufts of wheat and heather, and their borders of still denser copse, born more of the idea of property than of the earth itself.  Between the masses of landed property run the thin cataracts of road owned by the municipal state, and carved across the particular fields are the foot- and cart-worn paths of the serfs.  At the highest points of the land are perched the manors and mansions of the aristocracy.  Besides these positive aspects, there are, here and there, the numerous absences and silences of little note (in no particular order): no birds singing, no leaves on the trees, no scenes of animals, no centers of social commotion, no souls; and beyond that, just out of view, were the things that are not, in the end, actually there.
Above, scattered ranks of clouds pass by at an apparent 5-10 knots, and are the only suggestion to the eyes that time has not stopped. Behind this, the pale tablet of sky that forced itself onto the literary space in an unending, unwanted tryst ordained by God, punishing with a splitting pain in the forehead anyone who accidentally looks upwards. Maybe just one patch of blue sky behind the right shoulder of Christ Pantocrator who offers an enigmatic greeting from the cathedral zenith, framed by spiraling babies and saints. “Is He  flipping us off?” marvels the passing traveler. But no, Christ is not flipping us off.  The aural space, meanwhile, is occupied almost exclusively by the staccato gusts and blusters of the wind which all year do not cease accosting the face of land and people, and even seems to aspire to the totality of silence itself. And in those instances when the wind stops, one is overwhelmed by the silence which is even harder to hear; and to which one cannot close one’s ears.
These were some of the general elements describing, in broad strokes, the ambient sphere of rising action.
Now the light, spring britzka turned onto the drive of the estate and immediately there appeared on both sides of the road the tiny houses and barns where M. Manilov kept his souls. For reasons not yet revealed to the reader, Chichikov poked his head out of the window and began ticking divots in the air with his finger to keep count of the crumbling, dilapidated roofs and cracked windowpanes whence peered the pale gaunt faces of souls. A blast of wind, meanwhile, buffeted our hero’s sparse hairs and knocked the britzka from side to side like a little kettle on the stove!  “Blyat!” cursed Chichikov, withdrawing himself into the small carriage.
...Peered out from the vast, splitting, gray tablet of sky that God had ordained them to carry upon their backs everywhere they went...
Now the mansion appeared atop a knob in the distance, like a fly which suddenly alights atop a heap of shit,
Already the proprietor of the estate—a certain landowner of those parts, I believe I already mentioned his name, a certain Monsieur H—k, whose acquaintance Chichikov had had occasion to make at the recent governor’s soirée—could be seen standing on the steps of the front porch, holding his hand to his brow in a little arch to better shade his eyes.  He seemed to recognize the approaching britzka and a smile appeared on his face, which widened and widened as the britzka drew near the front steps, until at last it was as wide as the britzka that drew up before the front portico of the mansion.
“Ah!  Welcome dear Chichikov!” he called out, “So, you have not forgotten us after all!”
“Ah!  Welcome!” replied Chichikov.
“No, but it is you who are welcome here!”
“Welcome, thank you!” said Chichikov again, which was ridiculous because he was the one who had arrived.
“Ah!  But no, no, it is you alone who are welcome, dear Monsieur Chichikov!  This is my house, my offices, I daresay, and so you are the welcome one here…”
“But I am also insisting on welcoming you, your Excellency!”
“Ah, but most honorable Monsieur!  And now you will do me this great disservice?  Why, it is you who are deserving to be called ‘Excellency.’”
“Bah!  Nonsense!  I have neither rank nor title…”
“You have both.  And me?  What then am I, if you are nothing?  ‘Doctor’ perhaps, you may call me, but ‘Excellency?’  No, that is too far.”
“But I insist that you be called Excellency.  Or perhaps if there is some still more exalted title by which…”
“No, no, no!  It is I, it is I, my dear guest, who am forever indebted to you!” and with these words M. Manilov waved his arm back and forth with such force that Chichikov thought briefly that his host was being attacked by invisible bats. But when a moment or two had passed our hero understood, deftly, that this was for effect. Our hero knew there were not really any bats attacking M. Manilov, and he smiled amicably. And so the two gentlemen entered the house arm in arm; and the chestnut mare Assessor, who was harnessed to the britzka, held them in her gaze for the whole time it took them to climb the steps of the porch and enter the house; and then she shook her head and let out a loud snort, as animals do when they have witnessed strange scenes.
