A pleasantly dressed woman met them in the vestibule, to whom Manilov flew and, lifting up her delicate hands in his, announced tenderly, “My dove, Chichikov has visited us!” And the two love birds looked deeply into each other’s eyes and smiled exuberantly, as though learning they were heirs to an immeasurable fortune.
“I present to you my wife,” began Manilov, but Mrs. Manilov could not restrain herself, and started down a list of questions that she had carefully curated since Chichikov’s appearance at the governor’s soiree a week earlier: “And what is your opinion of our town of M.? And did you enjoy the governor’s soirée? And what do you think of our governor, and of our vice-governor, and of the  of phosphate fertilizer affair?  Did you have the chance to make their acquaintance?”
“As God is my witness, indeed I did.”
“And what about our councilor magistrate and actual privy chancellor of the strategic petrochemical reserve, and the vice postmaster secretary general of the regency of naval O-ring plant No. 119107?  Strategic Purpose Rocketry Troops. Did you have occasion to make their acquaintance?”
[“Oh yes,” said Chichikov, and drawing himself up he added, “Do you know it is not even that…  It is even…I have never really…hm’mmm!”]
“And what did you think of the new chancellor-secretary-at-arms, and the vice-comptroller of ?” said Mrs. Manilov, “I happen to maintain the highest opinion of their bearing, especially, and of their mannerliness.”
“Hm’mm,” responded Chichikov, knitting his brow into a thoughtful expression: “I found that particularly where mannerliness is regarded, you will not meet with gentlemen so staid and agreeable as the chancellor-secretary and vice-comptroller of .”
At this pronouncement, Mrs. Manilov [exhaled sharply] rested her line of inquiry inhaled deeply  was so enthralled by this masterful command of diction
“And what about our head magistrate-general, and our chief secretary-general of the majestry of naval constructions,” asked M. Manilov, narrowing his eyes slightly, after the manner of a cat that has been scratched behind the ears, “and the archlieutenant-ombudsman?  They have an especially agreeable aspect as regards meaningness, I find.”
“The head magistrate-general and archlieutenant-ombudsman?” repeated Chichikov for effect, holding himself perfectly upright and repeating the words at first, and then letting himself melt into a low and humble bow, and declaiming, “But they, Madame, no…they….” and then, although he knew no French, he threw in some French-sounding noises, and staggered a bit to the left and to the right, as though swooning beneath his recollection of the head magistrate-general and archlieutenant-ombudsman. Indeed, the host and hostess took Chichikov’s meaning without further words, nodding their heads in silent gravity.
The mood had grown very solemn; and the two gentlemen seemed to be so deeply moved that they could not proceed, until at last M. H— exclaimed:
“Yes, Chichikov!  The country and solitude are well enough, and books, but it would be a different thing altogether if one had a discursive partner—the sort of man with whom one can in some way discuss matters of amicability and good manners, so as to somehow stir the soul, to lend it, so to speak, a kind of soaring….”  And here he pulled a handkerchief from his pocket and dabbed at the mistiness in his eyes, and in a gust he concluded, “Oh, would that there were two of you—nay, a hundred, a thousand Chichikovs!—to bring me the light of restive intellect every day!”
“But no, your Excellency,” asserted Chichikov meanwhile, “on the contrary, I am convinced that I was led here by a certain agreeableness.  A genuine meaningness of amiability, such as is evident in your every bearing, is a beacon of light unto a weary traveler such as I….  Indeed, I am not at all unconvinced that our coming together is at all unlike the coming together of the three magi who were led on to Bethlehem by the star….  And with St. Phillip’s Feast so close at hand…”
No one knows what this sentimental duet [this mutual outpouring of sentiment] would have led to had not a servant entered just then to announce that dinner was ready, and the three nobles, who had been discussing the life of staidness, agreeableness, and mannerliness, bowed and saluted each other once more, and headed off towards the dining room.
Chichikov knew there was the one thing, and then the other things that were different from it, and that the two sets of things could never be the same as each other on account of their being different. He knew that it was the hallmark of things that were the same as each other that they would always, in the end, turn out to be one thing; even though they might upon first glance have appeared to have been different things that were not the same as each other, and vice versa; and that it was the penchant of agreeable gentlemen everywhere to ensure that this fundamental rule was never, under any circumstances, violated. It was the most obvious of axioms, was it not, that, wherever your light spring britzka may take you on the municipal roads of N., all things—for example, different sorts of leaves, bits of dirt and grass, certain pebbles, et cetera—were different from each other. Why, who would deny that the myriad complexity of Creation was reducible to this one thing: 1) that there many things, all of which were different from each other; 2) that all things that were not different from each other always without exception turned out in the end to be one and the same thing; and 3) all things that were different from each other were united by the common property of being different from each other, and were thus, in the strictest sense, indistinguishable from each other. En fin: There were two kinds of things in the world: the kind of things that were the same as each other, and the kind of things that were different from each other, which were the same insofar as they were different.
Or such were Chichikov’s musings at the dinner table, presented here in summarized form for the reader’s convenience—but every tender morsel of which Monsiuer and Madame Manilov devoured in long form, under the same rapt awe that Master Themistocleus, their ten year old boy, slurped up his soup—surrounded on two sides by servants who, with the precision of fencing masters, periodically lunged forth with napkins to catch the snot from his nose before it dripped into his soup.
When the dinner was concluded and Madame bid farewell and retired to her apartments, the two gentlemen repaired to Manilov’s study to deepen their discussion of matters of the highest import as regards agreeableness, staidness, mannerliness, and meaningness. Chichikov was offered a pipe and invited to sit upon a leather chair—whereupon he arrayed himself and immediately leaned forward in the most adroitly engaging fashion imaginable, his hands and pipe collected atop his knees in an elaborate cairn shape—while M. Manilov remained standing at the hearth, resting his head upon his hand and his elbow upon the mantelpiece, his pipe suspended at his waist in his other hand, staring in starstruck wonder at his guest. [He suspected as much since the governor’s soiree, but now there could be no doubt in his mind: most urbane etc.] Although he had made no inquiries as to his guest’s education, origins, or motives, Manilov was convinced by his bearing alone that Chichikov was the most urbane, entrepreneurial, well heeled, and widely traveled companion to pass through the little town of M. in a generation; and was eager to sip at the font of worldly wisdom that sat before him. Chichikov, for his part, did not disappoint, holding forth on matters of commerce, fashion trends, and upon certain experiments in magnetism recently published in one of our fine provincial academic journals.
Before either one of them knew it, the coals had died down, and the pipe smoke rose and took unknown shapes in the darkness above their heads; and Manilov strained his eyes to regard the hour, but hour and clockface had long been swallowed in the upturned shadow of the mantelpiece. Even so, it was possible to keep a time of sorts by marking the passage in terms of solemn pronouncements and amicable turns of phrase. The eyes of the two gentlemen deepened into little pools of flickering shadow, like murder weapons resting at the bottom of remote forest pools. Each successive utterance was a mannerly shell of, and difficult to tell apart from, the utterance that preceded it, but had no connection to the previous commentaries, nor to anything else in the world, as regards logic and meaning. [But the intervening silences dilated until this method was insufficient.    Manilov made as though to speak and mark the end of another measure of silence, but instead descended into a fit of coughing. Only the dancing pools of shadow were visible on his guest’s face, and not his guest’s face.; and Manilov pinched his lapels between thumb and forefinger in a fresh affectation at speech, instead descended into a fit of coughing.]
I could not help but notice, as I drew up to your estate, the many souls
Manilov was able to mark the evening’s passage by the intervals of silence punctuated by amicable utterances.  The successive utterance had little connection to the previous as regards meaning.
Manilov who stood by the mantel, peered into the darkness where Chichikov sat, trying to search his friend’s face for some hint at the hidden meaning that was no doubt at play in his question. But no hint was forthcoming. The coals had died down, and the eyes of the two gentlemen deepened into little pools of shadow that flickered and steadied, like murder weapons tossed into remote forest ponds. The smoke rose from their pipes and took unknown shapes in the darkness above their heads.

“But I cannot grasp…excuse me…I, of course, could not have received such a brilliant education as is perceivable in your every movement; I have no lofty art of expression...Here it may be…in this explanation just expressed by you…something else is concealed…It may be that you were pleased to express it thus for the beauty of the style?” “No,” said Chichikov, “I mean the matter just as I stated it—that is, those souls which have died, but who would, nonetheless, be counted on the census as living.”  At all of this M. Manilov remained silent for several moments, and brought his hand to his chin, where there was a little beard. “And for what reasons do you need this, Chichikov?”  “You ask, for what reasons?  These are the reasons:
At last Monsieur Manilov descended into a fit of laughter that was at once, somehow, glib and earnest; and Chichikov joined in with a light chuckle of his own, and the two laughters crescendoed and grew and intertwined in the darkness like the thin streams of smoke emitting from their pipes; while at the same time casting sidelong glances in each other’s direction and raising their glasses into the air. Then the chuckling tapered off and they were once again engulfed in the nothingness whence they had set out. M. Manilov struck a wistful gaze upon his fields, which were visible through the window beneath a light mist.  “And so then, if there are no obstacles, we might proceed then…with the purchase?”  “Purchase?”  “The dead souls, that is…”  “Ah!  But…”  And here Manilov gazed meaningly into Chichikov’s face to catch the ironic intent that was at play.  There was as a matter of fact no such ironic intent, but Manilov ignored this detail…Chichikov swooned and gave such a violent twitch in his seat that he nearly burst the fabric of the cushion beneath him.  Finally, he even gave a little leap after the manner of the goat, who are known to perform such leaps only under the strongest impulses of joy.


and Manilov pinched his lapels between thumb and forefinger in a fresh affectation at speech, instead descended into a fit of coughing.  For a long time the clock above the fireplace had been lost in the upturned shadow of the mantelpiece, and it had not been possible to tell the hour. Manilov had maintained a subconscious tally of the evening’s passage in terms of silent intervals between agreeable commentaries and clever turns of phrase.  These silences had gradually dilated,    Manilov made as though to speak and mark the end of another measure of silence, but instead   but was immediately checked by the disturbing sensation of not knowing how long the most recent silence had lasted, not knowing the hour, no longer being able to judge with any certainty for how long he had been staring absently into the consummate darkness.  And instead of the words he had formed his mouth to utter, he choked on a bit of his saliva and descended into a fit of coughing, whence he nearly did not extract himself.  Only the dancing pools of shadow were visible on his guest’s face, and not his guest’s face.




Chichikov knew there was the one, and then the other thing, that was not the same as the first one, and that the two could never, under any circumstances, be the same thing—on account of their being different from each other. He knew that this was true of all things, the fundamental unity of Creation, shared the fundamental property of being what they were, as opposed to being other things that were not what they were….and that all things were the same in this regard. Many a placid smile had spread across his face, upon many a country road, at the little clouds of pious foreknowledge that passed through his mind. of the fundamental unity of creation. It was the bedrock of the unflappable staidness that was the hallmark of his character, and that now trickled through the town of M. sure as melting snow.  [ there was no chance of the two things ever being the same so long as they were different from each other.] He knew the fundamental law that two things that were different from each other can never, under any circumstances, be the same thing. By the same token, any two things that were different from each other shared the fundamental property of being different from each other, and were thus the same precisely in the measure that they were different. Such convictions formed the bedrock of his unflappable staidness which spread like a flowing network of streams of life through the backwater town of M.
Things cannot be the absence of what they are. To imagine a world where it were not so was to imagine the abyss. That is, to remove the predicate for imagination. Go on and try—at your own risk! These were hard fought fruits of long years of staring out of dashed to pieces against the carriage frame on country roads, staring out of britzka windows.  the  was the secret to his unflinching staidness
